"Mendelssohn R., Bograd S.J., Schwing F.B., Palacios D.M.","Teaching old indices new tricks: A state-space analysis of El Niño related climate indices",2005,"Geophysical Research Letters","32","7",,"1","4",,,10.1029/2005GL022350,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-21844459263&partnerID=40&md5=7ae38f7ec0e33e5bcad94a48c9b579b6","Pacific Fisheries Environmental Laboratory, Southwest Fisheries Science Center, 1352 Lighthouse Avenue, Pacific Grove, CA 93950, United States","Mendelssohn, R., Pacific Fisheries Environmental Laboratory, Southwest Fisheries Science Center, 1352 Lighthouse Avenue, Pacific Grove, CA 93950, United States; Bograd, S.J., Pacific Fisheries Environmental Laboratory, Southwest Fisheries Science Center, 1352 Lighthouse Avenue, Pacific Grove, CA 93950, United States; Schwing, F.B., Pacific Fisheries Environmental Laboratory, Southwest Fisheries Science Center, 1352 Lighthouse Avenue, Pacific Grove, CA 93950, United States; Palacios, D.M., Pacific Fisheries Environmental Laboratory, Southwest Fisheries Science Center, 1352 Lighthouse Avenue, Pacific Grove, CA 93950, United States","State-space models were applied to several climate indices associated with the El Niño-Southern Oscillation (ENSO), including the Southern Oscillation Index (SOI) and its component sea level pressure series; the NINO3 sea surface temperature index; and the Northern Oscillation Index (NOI). The best models for each series include a significant long-term nonparametric trend combined with a stochastic stationary cyclic term that clearly delineates the El Niño and La Niña events. There is no evidence that the frequency of ENSO events has changed over the 20th century. The long-term trend, however, has contributed to an apparent increase in the magnitude of recent El Niño events. This trend, potentially related to global warming, has increased the level of each series by an amount equal to 30-50% of the amplitude of their corresponding annual cycle or cyclic ENSO term. Thus, the background sea surface temperature in the eastern equatorial Pacific is more than 0.5°C warmer now than prior to 1950, implying a greater overall impact of El Niño events.",,"Climatology; Global warming; Mathematical models; Oceanography; Oscillations; Stochastic control systems; Temperature distribution; El Niño-Southern Oscillation (ENSO); Northern oscillation index (NOI); Sea surface temperature; Southern oscillation index (SOI); State space methods; climate modeling; El Nino-Southern Oscillation; sea level pressure; sea surface temperature",,,,,,"Akaike, H., Information theory and an extension of the maximum likelihood principle (1973) Second International Symposium on Information Theory, pp. 267-281. , edited by B. N. Petrov and F. Csaki, Akademiai Kiado, Budapest; An, S., Interdecadal changes in the El Nino-La Nina asymmetry (2004) Geophys. Res. Lett., 31, pp. L23210. , doi:10.1029/2004GL021699; Durbin, J., Koopman, S.J., (2001) Time Series Analysis By State-Space Methods, p. 253. , Oxford Univ. Press, New York; Harrison, D.E., Larkin, N.K., Darwin sea level pressure, 1876-1996: Evidence for climate change? (1997) Geophys. Res. Lett., 24, pp. 1779-1782; Harvey, A.C., (1989) Forecasting, Structural Time Series Models, and the Kalman Filter, p. 554. , Cambridge Univ. Press, New York; Harvey, A.C., Koopman, S.J., Diagnostic checking of unobserved components time series models (1992) J. Bus. Econ. Stat., 10, pp. 377-389; Horel, J., Wallace, J.M., Planetary-scale atmospheric phenomena associated with the Southern Oscillation (1981) Mon. Weather Rev., 109, pp. 813-829; Koopman, S.J., Harvey, A.C., Doornik, J.A., Shephard, N., (2000) STAMP 6.0: Structural Time Series Analyser, Modeler, and Predictor, p. 203. , Timberlake Consult., London; Mann, M.E., Gille, E.P., Bradley, R.S., Hughes, M.K., Overpeck, J.T., Keimig, F.T., Gross, W.S., Global temperature patterns in past centuries: An interactive presentation (2000) IGBP Pages/World Data Cent. Paleoclim